Date: 7 Nov 2004
From: Jim Turner <jt_graphics_cad@yahoo.com>
Source: Pune newswire of Express India, 25 Oct 2004 [sent/accessed 7 Nov
2004, edited]
<http://cities.expressindia.com/fullstory.php?newsid=104644>

Child deaths: NIV scientists in UP
-----------------------------------
Reports of a mysterious disease stalking children in several districts of
western Uttar Pradesh has activated the city-based National Institute of
Virology (NIV) to dispatch a team of scientists to collect samples and work
towards a proper diagnosis of the virus.
A team of 3 senior scientists are already in Uttar Pradesh, while another
team left on Monday [25 Oct 2004], Dr. G Varghese, NIV's officiating
officer-in-charge, told Pune Newsline.
So far, at least 48 children have succumbed to the mysterious disease
traced to Sahranpur, Noida, Ghaziabad, and Bulandshahr. This was after
about 100 children were admitted to several health government care centers
and hospitals at Meerut, Muzaffarnagar, and Garhmukteshwar districts with
complaints of severe headache, fever, and vomiting. But, the children found
to be infected with the deadly virus displayed symptoms similar to
meningitis and cholera.
NIV scientists are supposed to collect samples and come back to Pune for
investigation. Serology and other tests will be conducted, and the findings
will be confirmed with a Polymerase Chain Reaction (PCR) test, Dr. Varghese
said.
--
